<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oranensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea oranensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but immediately distinguished by the hypocratiform corolla with a cylindrical tube and exserted genitalia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Both 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="exserta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea exserta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oranensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. oranensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have some stellate hairs mixed with unbranched hairs but these are often difficult to see. The two species may sometimes grow together but 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="oranensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. oranensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found most commonly at higher altitudes, from 1600 to 2200 m, although there are a few records from as low as 650 m.
</paragraph>
